en end up disempowering women, transforming their social vulnerabilities into personal pathologies, and pushing them into a state of disentitlement. Uncovering the complex gendered underpinning of methods of control and intervention used in the criminal justice system today, Offending Women links that system to broader discussions on contemporary government and state power, asks why these strategies have arisen at this particular moment in time, and considers what forms of citizenship they have given rise to.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aCorrectional institutions -- California -- Case studies. 0aCorrectional institutionsxCase studiesxCaliforniaxCalifornia. 0aCorrectional institutionszCaliforniavCase studies. 0aElectronic books. -- local. 0aFemale offenders -- California -- Case studies. 0aFemale offenders -- Rehabilitation -- California -- Case studies. 0aFemale offendersxCase studiesxCalifornia. 0aFemale offendersxCase studiesxRehabilitationxCalifornia. 0aFemale offendersxRehabilitationzCaliforniavCase studies. 0aFemale offenderszCaliforniavCase studies. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Gender Studies.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook Package 2000-2015z978311066334108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311069042240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520945913423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780520945913.jpg  a978-3-11-066334-1  UC Press eBook Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  a978-3-11-069042-2  UC Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles